$\begin{aligned}
& f(x)=x^4+1+\frac{1}{x^2+x+1}=\text { even degree polynomial + bounded function } \frac{1}{x^2+x+1} \in\left(0, \frac{4}{3}\right) \\
& f^{\prime}(x)=\frac{4 x^3\left(x^2+x+1\right)^2-2 x-1}{\left(x^2+x+1\right)^2}
\end{aligned}$
$\Rightarrow f^{\prime}(x)=0$ has atleast one root which is repeated odd number of times or it has one root which is not repeated since numerator of $f^{\prime}(x)$ is a polynomial of degree 7 .
$\Rightarrow f(x)=0$ has a point of extrema.
